    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "ca53514e_d0f29975",
        "filename": "client/crashpad_client_ios.cc",
        "patchSetId": 2
      },
      "lineNbr": 122,
      "author": {
        "id": 1174099
      },
      "writtenOn": "2020-04-22T16:08:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You’re also missing EXC_SYSCALL, which can appear. EXC_MACH_SYSCALL is unused but I think we’d want to include it too as it’s part of the family.\n\nYou should make sure to sort in the order of \u003cmach/exception_types.h\u003e.\n\nIt may be more reasonable to do ExcMaskAll() and mask OUT the bits that you don’t want, like\n\nExcMaskAll() \u0026 ~(EXC_MASK_BREAKPOINT | EXC_MASK_RPC_ALERT | EXC_MASK_GUARD)\n\n(not saying which of these you’ll definitely want or not want.)\n\nPost-scripts are informative, preemptively answering questions:\n\nP.S. you don’t want EXC_RPC_ALERT, it was unused and recycled for Shark/Instruments performance monitoring stuff, and we don’t want it. See 10.15.0 xnu-6153.11.26/osfmk/kern/exception.c sys_perf_notify and xnu-6153.11.26/osfmk/kern/ux_handler.c ux_handler_setup.\n\nP.P.S. to trigger EXC_SYSCALL, set up a call to a Mach trap, but use a trap number that doesn’t exist. That works on x86, at least. xnu-6153.11.26/osfmk/i386/bsd_i386.c mach_call_munger[64], xnu-6153.11.26/osfmk/x86_64/idt64.s hndl_syscall, hndl_diag_scall64. I don’t see a way to get EXC_SYSCALL on ARM. Doesn’t mean we shouldn’t register for it.\n\nP.P.P.S. I’ve left out EXC_SOFTWARE. It used to be possible to trigger EXC_SOFTWARE by asking the CPU to execute a BOUND instruction that failed the bounds check, but that instruction was removed from x86_64. That could have been something that an application would want for its own purposes, we might not want to treat it as a crash (although I’d have to go back in time to double-check, if it was important). I don’t know if it’s possible to generate an EXC_SOFTWARE like that on ARM at all, but the kernel doesn’t seem to have anything. There are EXC_SOFTWARE exceptions that are supposed to tell debuggers about exceptions (xnu-2782.40.9/bsd/kern/kern_sig.c issignal_locked) but we don’t need that, we can get real Mach exceptions and signals directly. There are EXC_SOFTWARE exceptions that can be generated for security reasons (xnu-2782.40.9/security/mac_base.c mac_do_machexc), but I don’t think we can catch those, they’re also more for debuggers. Also, we can’t see the callers without reverse-engineering MACFramework.kext. So I think we shouldn’t camp out on this one.\n\nP.P.P.P.S. EXC_EMULATION is meant for something like “this CPU doesn’t implement that instruction, fake it in software.” It would have been used in olden days to do things like software fallback for floating-point instructions when there wasn’t any hardware floating-point unit, back when this might have been running on a system that didn’t have one. Most dinosaurs didn’t have much use for anything but integer arithmetic. Don’t think we need this one, because if it ever becomes relevant again, it wouldn’t be “crashy” unless there was no software fallback in place.",
      "revId": "9f4b9d892532481994c06d20b08436ed6e158fe5",
      "serverId": "3ce6091f-6c88-37e8-8c75-72f92ae8dfba",
      "unresolved": true
